    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The \"why\" of quantum entanglement is one of the most intriguing aspects of quantum physics, and it's still a subject of much research and debate. When a measurement is made on one of the entangled particles, the wave function of the entire system collapses instantaneously, and the state of the other particle is determined, regardless of the distance between them. This instantaneous connection is often referred to as \"spooky action at a distance\" by Albert Einstein, who was skeptical of the phenomenon.\n\nThe exact mechanism behind this instantaneous connection is not fully understood and is a topic of ongoing research. Some theories suggest that it may be due to the entangled particles being part of a single, unified quantum system, while others propose that it may be a result of hidden variables that we have yet to discover.\n\nIn addition to being called \"spooky action at a distance,\" quantum entanglement is also referred to as \"quantum nonlocality\" or \"quantum correlation.\" These terms highlight the non-local nature of the phenomenon, where the entangled particles are connected in a way that defies classical intuition and our everyday understanding of the world.\n\nIt's important to note that while quantum entanglement is a well-established phenomenon, it still challenges our",
      "source": "target",
